They really did! Especially SunSoft, if you didn't already know they created some of the most incredible 8 bit games. By the way, are you aware of why SunSoft games tend to have very much depth for being NES games? It's because they uniquely used the DPCM saple sound channel to get that awesome "SunSoft bass" 
DPCM samples are basically compressed real life sounds that are played back by the CPU.

text:
If that was the case at all, it wasn't in the western versions of the game since the NES does not support external microprocessors.

The Japanese Famicom however, did. Konami was one of the companies making use of this with the so-called VCR6-chip, which was used for games like Castlevania 3. It only added two noise channels to the mix though, so don't expect SNES-quality from that game either.
